  <section id="healthcare-system">
    <h2>Healthcare System Overview</h2>
    <p>
      New Zealand's healthcare is excellent—well-organized, high-quality, and comparable to other developed countries. Understanding the system helps maximize its benefits.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Public healthcare:</strong> Funded through taxation and provides comprehensive care for residents and citizens. District Health Boards manage regional services. Quality is good, though waiting times for elective procedures can be significant. Emergency and essential care is excellent.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Private healthcare:</strong> Supplements the public system with faster access, private rooms, and choice of specialists. Major private hospitals include Southern Cross Hospitals, Mercy Hospital, and others. Private insurance enables this faster track.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Major hospitals:</strong> Auckland City Hospital, Wellington Hospital, and Christchurch Hospital are major public facilities with comprehensive capabilities. These handle complex procedures, trauma, and serious conditions. Quality approaches major international standards.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>GP system:</strong> General practitioners serve as gatekeepers to specialist care. Enrolling with a GP practice provides ongoing primary care. Costs for non-subsidized patients are NZ$50-100 per visit.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Prescription medications:</strong> Pharmac (government agency) manages pharmaceutical subsidies. Subsidized medications are very affordable for eligible patients. Non-subsidized medications cost more but are available at pharmacies throughout the country.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Remote areas:</strong> South Island's remote regions have limited healthcare—serious conditions require transfer to major centers. Helicopter rescue services are well-developed for remote area emergencies.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="costs">
    <h2>Cost Planning</h2>
    <p>
      New Zealand is expensive—among the priciest retirement destinations, comparable to or exceeding many European countries. Currency is the New Zealand dollar (NZD).
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Total monthly budget</strong> for comfortable retirement with comprehensive health coverage typically ranges from NZ$4,500-7,500 depending on location and lifestyle. Auckland comfortable retirement runs NZ$5,500-7,500; Wellington NZ$5,000-7,000; regional areas NZ$4,000-6,000.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Currency equivalent:</strong> At typical exchange rates, comfortable New Zealand retirement costs US$2,800-4,700/month—significantly more than most destinations covered in this guide. New Zealand is a developed-world-cost destination.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Healthcare costs:</strong> Insurance runs NZ$600-1,000/month for seniors with comprehensive coverage. Non-residents pay full costs for public healthcare without subsidies—hospital stays can cost thousands. Adequate insurance is essential.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Housing dominates costs:</strong> New Zealand property is expensive relative to incomes. Auckland is particularly costly. Regional areas offer better value but fewer services. Housing is the largest expense category.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="faqs">
    <h2>Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 mt-6">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Can I retire to New Zealand without family there?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Difficult. Without New Zealand citizen/resident children, Australian citizenship, or substantial investment capacity (NZ$3-15 million), pathways to residence are limited. Many would-be retirees are disappointed by New Zealand's restrictive immigration.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How does New Zealand healthcare compare to US/UK?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Comparable quality, differently organized. Public system provides comprehensive care with some waiting times. Private system offers faster access. Overall quality is high—New Zealand handles most conditions locally without evacuation concerns.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is New Zealand really that expensive?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes. Housing, food, and services cost comparable to or more than Western Europe. The strong NZ dollar compounds this for foreign retirees. Budget NZ$4,500-7,500/month for comfortable retirement. This is a developed-world destination at developed-world costs.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What about earthquakes?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">New Zealand is seismically active—major earthquakes occur periodically (Christchurch 2010-2011 was devastating). Building codes are strict, and emergency systems are well-developed. Risk exists but is managed. Consider earthquake insurance for property.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is New Zealand isolated?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Geographically yes—far from everywhere. Australia is the nearest developed country (3+ hours by air). Flights to Europe/Americas take 12-24 hours. This isolation suits some retirees, bothers others. Consider whether remoteness matters to you.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What's the climate like?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Temperate with regional variation. North Island is warmer; South Island cooler. Auckland has mild, humid climate. South Island can be quite cold in winter. No extreme heat. Weather is changeable—"four seasons in one day" is the local saying.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Plan Your New Zealand Retirement?"
    description="Get personalized quotes from insurers meeting New Zealand visa requirements. Coverage for one of the world's best quality-of-life destinations."
    buttonText="Get Your Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />
</PageShell>
